5|$|The {{proper motion}} {{of a star}} is its amount of {{movement}} across the <b>celestial</b> <b>sphere,</b> determined by comparing its position relative to more distant background objects. Tau Ceti {{is considered to be}} a high-proper-motion star, although it only has an annual traverse of just under two arc seconds.|$|E
5|$|The {{ecliptic}} is {{the circular}} path on the <b>celestial</b> <b>sphere</b> that the Sun appears to follow {{over the course}} of a year; it is the basis of the ecliptic coordinate system. The term also refers to the plane of this path, which is coplanar with Earth's orbit around the Sun (and hence the Sun's apparent orbit around Earth).|$|E
5|$|Although {{the astronomical}} armillary sphere (representing the <b>celestial</b> <b>sphere)</b> existed in China since the 1st century BCE, the {{mathematician}} and court astronomer Zhang Heng (78–139 CE) provided it with motive power {{by using the}} constant pressure head of an inflow water clock to rotate a waterwheel that acted {{on a set of}} gears. Zhang Heng was also the first {{to address the problem of}} the falling pressure head in the inflow water clock (which gradually slowed the timekeeping) by setting up an additional tank between the reservoir and inflow vessel.|$|E
