5|$|Edward Grant, a {{historian}} of science, {{has provided evidence}} that medieval scholastic philosophers generally considered the <b>celestial</b> <b>spheres</b> to be solid {{in the sense of}} three-dimensional or continuous, but most did not consider them solid in the sense of hard. The consensus was that the <b>celestial</b> <b>spheres</b> were made of some kind of continuous fluid.|$|R
